AB  - [This essay examines the relatively overlooked speculative short fiction included in W.E.B. Du Bois's Darkwater (1920): “The Princess of the Hither Isles,” “Jesus Christ in Texas,” and “The Comet.” I read these pieces in Darkwater through the lens of “racial impossibility” to discern the interconnectedness between Du Bois's fiction and his political theory in order to explore the role that his creative writing played in his imaginations of social change. I argue that Du Bois's fictional writings are not merely illustrations of his utopian thought but rather where it emerges. Specifically, it is precisely the failures of these fictions in imagining utopia that can be read as moments of political refusal that helped him cultivate his political theories.]
