AB  - Philip K. Dick brought to science fiction a vision of reality that does not easily differentiate between objective fact and delusion. Ragle Gumm, the protagonist of Time Out of Joint (1959), straddles that unstable boundary: he finds himself living in a phony world that has been created out of his own neurosis, simultaneously perpetrator and victim of a compelling deformation of reality. An important precedent for this character and his situation is Miguel de Cervantes's Don Quixote de la Mancha (1605-1615), the first work of fiction that systematically conflates obsessive fabulation and disinterested 'truth.' This essay reads PKD through Don Quixote in order to define the sf writer's contribution to the Cervantean tradition of the modern novel.
