AB  - C.L. Moore's 'Shambleau,' too often read as a symptom of Moore's supposed self-alienation or self-loathing, is here read alongside later origin-narratives based on 'Shambleau' by Moore herself and Lester del Rey. Employing Donna Haraway's critical framework of the cyborg, which links issues of technology, gender, subjectivity, and the process of retelling origin stories, I suggest that 'Shambleau' can be read less dismissively as a story which exposes the dominant discourses' reliance upon a narrative of the Fall of language which defines the feminine as both marginal and subject to masculine control. Central to this reading are the intersections of technology and gender which resonate between Moore's story and Moore's own narration of her story's origins and which suggest that the re-narration of origin stories is a process central to feminist sf.
