AB  - Since the 1960s Samuel Delany's work has frequently been at the speculative edge of 'soft' science, feminism, and post-humanist thought. Its equally ongoing concern with mythology moves from '60s resistance of white patriarchal heterosexual myths to their denial, deconstruction, and, with Dhalgren, demolition of myths and their generating system together. In the Nevèr on cycle postmodern theory informs the construction of a new (form of) mythology. Derridean theory supplies the 'Symbolic Order' of the cycle's blurred margins and centerless structure, while Foucault's use of S/M experience is paralleled in the series' 'homoerotic Imaginary.' Its eroticizing and mythicizing fantasies transgress generic and cultural boundaries in a manner characteristic of Delany's earlier sf, but here they also demonstrate the crucial interventions of postmodern theory in a work about Foucauldian 'limit-experiences' that becomes a 'limit-experience' in itself.
