AB  - The science-fiction film seems grounded in a constant tension between the speculative and the visceral, between our hopes for what might be and our very human-and physical-fears of what such developments could entail. The recent British film 'Hardware' particularly reflects this tension. In fact, it foregrounds that tension by 'quoting' numerous other science- fiction and horror films-by a sort of collage strategy that enables it to frame key questions about the nature of the science-fiction genre, about the technology from which it draws its life, and about what audiences expect from such films. In its reflexive treatment of what has become a commonplace of recent science-fiction films, that is, a deadly confrontation between humans and a humanly-crafted/human-destroying robot, 'Hardware' not only raises the usual concerns about the fragile nature of humanity and the threatening potential of our technology; it also suggests how our films-themselves a product of technological craft-can help us deal with those concerns by drawing on that generic tension to better 'frame,' as Heidegger put it, our humanness.
