AB  - Hailed by its authors, many of its critics, and its promoters within the SF publishing industry as 'preparing the ground for a revolution,' the cyberpunk SF of the 1980s has made large political claims for itself. Some of those claims are implicit in the determination of cyberpunk's authors to legitimize their revolutionary status through establishing a filial link with the SF fathers of the 1960s. But in making such connections, writers like Bruce Sterling have avoided (inadvertently?) all references to the political SF of the '70s, realized in the writings of feminists like Joanna Russ, Ursula Le Guin, Suzy McKee Charnas, and others. Sterling, for example, maintains that SF was in 'hibernation' in the 1970s. Such a pronounced lacuna is provocative, not only for what it reveals about the political space cyberpunk sees itself as occupying, but also for what it suggests with regard to its gender politics. This paper examines the nature of that supposedly revolutionary agenda in cyberpunk, first placing it within the context of its immediate feminist antecedents, then raising a number of questions as to its peculiar reliance on specific cultural icons popular in the Reaganite America of the 1980s.
