AB  - The contrast of Wells and Zamiatin involves two fundamental models in science fiction. Zamiatin in +Herbert Wells= (1922) eulogized Wells as a modernist writer, and gave voice to his own revolutionary esthetics. Nonetheless, Wells in his scientific romances was no 'modernist,' but an influential adapter of humanistic, Enlightenment narrative forms. In +We= (1920-21), Zamiatin abandoned Wells's reliance on the consciousness of the rational observer, and matched his portrayal of a future society with a futuristic fictional technique. Using a diary-form and a splintered, expressionistic style, Zamiatin revealed the social conflicts of his future State through the medium of its conflicting modes of consciousness and of language. +We= thus transcends the mannerism and formal conventionality of today's SF, exploring the paradox of a form that undertakes to express the increasingly alien. While more recent anti-utopian fiction becomes an appendage of contemporary realism, Wells and Zamiatin wrote future fantasies which, in different ways, go beyond social criticism to a probing of rational epistemological assumptions.
