AB  - A 'classic' of modern science fiction, Clarke's 1953 +Childhood's End= represents many virtues and vices of its genre. Weaving together technological extrapolation, utopian and dystopian speculation, e.s.p., and the contact between humans and extraterrestrial intelligences, +Childhood's End= is unified by its elegiac tone, its echoing and expanding image-patterns, and its theme: the next stage of evolution for mankind. The manipulation of mythic symbolism, however, on which Clarke's evocation of the 'sense of wonder' depends, sets up a morality play context, between God and the Devil, which undercuts his explicit emphasis on the powers of reason. The literate reader may also be put off by Clarke's seeming inattention to the means by which a writer must communicate his vision. The style is persistently banal, many individual scenes are inadequate to bear the weight of the 'cosmic viewpoint,' and plot and character are developed sketchily at best. An ambitious effort, it has a high seriousness unusual in pulp fiction, but it barely lives up to its name: +Childhood's End= does not represent a mature stage of science fiction.
