AB  - Annotates the content of 113 H. G. Wells's books and pamphlets. They are dealt with as abstract units rather than physical objects, and both omnibus collections and booklets and pamphlets that later appear as chapters or sections of full-size books are ignored. With exception allowed for any work that appears in the Atlantic Edition, early textbooks, or pamphlets to which Wells was merely a contributor, and pamphlets printed for private circulation issued as advertising brochures, or of less than 32 pages are also ignored. The length of each work is given in the pages of the Atlantic Edition or in the abstract pages of the same size. The book-length fictions are classified as novel or romance, and the romances are subclassified as science fiction, fantasy, ruritanian romance, etc. All the short stories and many of the essays are separately annotated, with the stories classified as mundane, science fiction, fantasy etc. The annotations are intended to be factually descriptive as to content and reputation, and are designed to show the intercalations between the various works and both the continuities and the changes in Wells's thought.
