AB  - Abstracts the science journalism that Wells wrote before 1900, items abstracted, 60 have been attributed to Wells by G. H. Wells or Gordon Ray, and the remaining 30, mostly from the +Pall Mall Gazette=, have been added after sifting that paper from August 1893 through May 1895 (the inclusive dates of Wells's contributions to it) and checking the results against the cue-sheets preserved in the University of Illinois Wells Archive, Urbana. Taken together, these 90 essays and reviews fall into three types, one dealing with science education and popularization, one with the wonders and mysteries revealed by science, and one with the unorthodox or paradoxical scientific speculations. Interesting in itself, the work as a whole also reveals that Wells's model of what good science writing should be closely parallels the methods that he transposed to the fictional frame of science short stories and scientific romances.
