AB  - A reading of +Starship= which discloses abrupt shifts in 'generic expectations' suggests that this form, a collage of successive and relatively unrelated types of narrative, may be a privileged one for science fiction and may provide a more adequate way of defining the latter's structure than the older opposition between realism and fantasy. At the same time, in Aldiss' book, the structure (the author's rapid shifts in genre) is projected onto the axis of content in the form of the theme of manipulation, and the final generic twist in Aldiss' work reveals the underlying political basis of the novel, which would appear to express a repressed anxiety about the relationship of advanced countries to underdeveloped ones.
