AB  - In response to Blish's claim that science fiction is the literature of change and thus has the function of making its readers better able to face the future, Rottensteiner argues that English-language science fiction serves no such function in any realistic way, since it ignores Marxism, the science of change and the official philosophy of millions of the world's inhabitants. Blish, while citing some exceptions, accepts the general truth of the charge of ignoring Marxism, most science-fiction writers being antipathetic to official philosophies of any kind. Le Guin, while sympathetic to Rottensteiner's position, deplores the tone of his attack, fearing that it points toward closed rather than open universes. Franklin charges that most American and English science-fiction writers have not only ignored but actively opposed Marxism and given full support to Western imperialism. Davis, speaking as an American science-fiction writer influenced by Marxism, grants that he and his fellow writers have tended to pose social concepts rather than to confront them, and thus to be trivial rather than serious, but warns against official doctrines: "Governmental apologetics are not always false, but they are always one-sided."
